## VII. THE LANGUAGES AS ANGLES INSIGHT

**"Different languages are different angles with different furniture"**

In the sandbox, we can visualize this:

```typescript
interface LanguageAngle {
  name: string
  rotationDegrees: number  // 0°, 60°, 120°, 180°, 240°, 300° (6 major languages)
  vocabulary: 'furniture' | 'architecture' | 'geometry'  // Same concepts, different words
}

const LANGUAGES = [
  { name: 'English', rotation: 0, vocab: 'furniture' },
  { name: 'Chinese', rotation: 60, vocab: 'architecture' },
  { name: 'Arabic', rotation: 120, vocab: 'geometry' },
  { name: 'Sanskrit', rotation: 180, vocab: 'furniture' },
  { name: 'Greek', rotation: 240, vocab: 'architecture' },
  { name: 'Hebrew', rotation: 300, vocab: 'geometry' },
]

// SAME SCENE, rotated by language-angle
function renderInLanguage(scene: Scene, language: LanguageAngle) {
  // Rotate the entire view by language angle
  scene.camera.rotation.z = language.rotationDegrees * (Math.PI / 180)

  // Use language-specific labels
  scene.labels.forEach(label => {
    label.text = translate(label.concept, language.name)
  })

  // Render
  scene.render()
}
```

**The user sees**:
- Same geometry (Flower of Life grid, Π-frames, NPCs)
- Same behavior (PLATO cycles, 60-vectors)
- Different perspective angle (rotated view)
- Different labels (translated terms)

**The "different furniture" = Different object names for same geometric archetypes**:
- English "table" = Chinese "桌" = Arabic "طاولة" = All refer to "horizontal plane at waist height supported by vertical legs" (Π-frame)

